text: Eur Biophys J DOI 10.1007/s00249-015-1073-2 Molecular level understanding of resistance to nalidixic acid  in Salmonella enteric serovar typhimurium associates   with the S83F sequence type B. Preethi1 · K. Ramanathan1  Received: 27 February 2015 / Revised: 15 July 2015 / Accepted: 12 August 2015  © European Biophysical Societies’ Association 2015 Abstract  Nalidixic  acid  is  an  antibiotic  drug  used  for  treatment  of  Salmonellosis,  a  gastrointestinal  infection.  DNA gyrase subunit A (GyrA) of Salmonella typhimurium  is the drug target for nalidixic acid. Resistance of GyrA to  nalidixic  acid,  because  of  a  point  mutation  in  S.  typhimu- rium, was recently reported. Substitution of Phe in place of  Ser at locus 83 in GyrA of S. typhimurium has been experi- mentally associated with nalidixic acid resistance. Despite  recent efforts, the mechanism of this resistance is not well  understood.  In  this  investigation  we  used  computational  techniques to address this shortcoming. Our results showed  that contact with residue Arg 91 is certainly important for  efficient binding of nalidixic acid to the target protein, and  that mutation of this residue results in 180° rotation of the  antibiotic  in  its  binding  pocket,  around  its  own  long  axis.  It is hoped these findings may enable development of new  antibiotics against resistant forms of Salmonella. Keywords  GyrA · Molecular docking · Molecular  dynamics simulation · Nalidixic acid · Salmonellosis Salmonella,  a  Gram-negative  bacterium,  is  one  of  the  important microbes responsible for both typhoid and non- typhoid  infections.  It  belongs  to  the  Enterobacteriaceae  family.  Salmonella  are  sub-divided  into  six  groups  and

Industrial Biotechnology Division, School of Bio Sciences  and Technology, VIT University, Vellore 632014,   Tamil Nadu, India approximately 2500 serovars have been identified, 99 % of  which are responsible for disease (Bopp et al.  2003). Sal- monella can cause different syndromes, for example gastro- enteritis,  enteric  fever,  and  septicemia.  Salmonella  enteric  serovar typhimurium is a food-borne pathogen which leads  to  salmonellosis  and  gastrointestinal  infections.  Approxi- mately  93.8  million  patients  have  been  reported  with  gas- troenteritis,  and  approximately  155,000  deaths  of  non- typhoid  patients  are  reported  annually  around  the  globe  (Majowicz et al. 2010). Non-typhoid Salmonella infections  are  emerging  in  both  developing  and  developed  countries  because  of  global  trade  and  food  exchange  (Esaki  et  al.  2004; Fisher and Threlfall 2005; Wong et al. 2011). Envi- ronmental  risk  factors,  for  example  poor  sanitation,  over- population, and food and water contamination, can lead to  salmonellosis (Crump and Mintz 2010).

Antimicrobial  agents,  for  example  ampicillin,  chloram- phenicol, and co-trimoxazole, with or without tetracycline,  were  used  in  the  twentieth  century  for  treatment  of  sal- monella  infection  (Sirinavin  and  Garner  2000).  Increased  isolation  of  multi-drug-resistant  species  now  limits  use  of  these drugs, however (Saha et al. 1992; Pillai and Prakash  1993).  Subsequently,  two  broad  ranges  of  antibacterial  agents,  the  quinolones  and  fluoroquinolones,  have  been  regarded  as  the  drugs  of  choice  in  treatment,  owing  to  resistance  that  appeared  during  the  1980s  (Hassing  et  al.  2011, 2013). These antimicrobial agents are highly active,  particularly against Enterobacteriaceae (Robert et al. 2001;  Ronald  and  Low  2003;  Satish  et  al.  2012).  However,  the  efficacy  of  antimicrobial  therapy  has  been  substantially  affected by an increase in the number of quinolone-resist- ant  salmonella  isolates  (Soto  et  al.  2003;  Piddock  et  al.  2010). The  frequent  use  of  fluoroquinolones,  particularly  cip- rofloxacin,  has  led  to  the  global  emergence  of  nalidixic

acid-resistant  salmonella  strains  (Mohanty  et  al.  2006;  Menezes  et  al.  2011; WHO  2012).  Most  importantly,  iso- lates  with  nalidixic  acid  resistance  have  reduced  suscepti- bility to ciprofloxacin, resulting in increased treatment fail- ure (Oteo et al. 2000). The global increase in the prevalence  of Salmonella strains with resistance to nalidixic acid is a  major  health  concern.  Literature  evidence  indicates  that  quinolone  resistance  of  Salmonella  spp.  is  mostly  attrib- uted  to  mutations  in  the  quinolone  resistance-determining  regions (QRDR) of the target enzymes DNA gyrase (gyrA  and gyrB) and topoisomerase IV (parC and parE) (Cloec- kaert and Chaslus-Dancla 2001; Piddock 2002; Velge et al.  2005;  Giraud  et  al.  2006).  In  particular,  for  DNA  gyrase,  a  single  mutation  resulting  in  amino  acid  substitution  at  position  83  (Ser  to  Phe  or  to  Tyr)  or  at  position  87  (Asp  to Asn  or  Gly)  has  been  most  frequently  reported  in  nali- dixic acid resistance isolates (Baucheron et al. 2014). The  evidence also indicates that the S83F mutation occurs most  frequently  and  is  observed  to  result  in  high  nalidixic  acid  resistance  (Cloeckaert  and  Chaslus-Dancla  2001;  Zheng  et al. 2009).

It  has  been  reported  that  binding  of  nalidixic  acid  to  the gyrase/topoisomerase IV-DNA complex inhibits DNA  replication.  This  action  is  responsible  for  the  bacterio- static and bactericidal property of quinolones, in particu- lar nalidixic acid. Mutations in the DNA gyrase and topoi- somerase IV may confer resistance to nalidixic acid, and  it has been shown that altered structures of these enzymes  prevent binding of quinolones (Ruiz 2003; Michael et al.  2006). Despite this literature evidence, the mechanism of  resistance  to  nalidixic  acid  at  the  molecular  level  is  not  completely  understood.  This  issue  could  be  addressed  with  advanced  computational  techniques.  The  purpose  of  this  study  was  to  focus  on  a  molecular-level  under- standing of the characteristics of nalidixic acid resistance  because  of  the  S83F  mutation  by  using  computational  techniques.  We  hope  the  results  will  provide  important  information enabling the development of lead compounds  with therapeutic effects against drug-resistant S. typhimu- rium strains. The  GyrA  of  the  Escherichia  coli  crystal  structure  was  retrieved  from  the  Protein  Data  Bank  (PDB)  (Ber- man  et  al.  2000).  The  corresponding  PDB  code  is  2Y3P  (Edwards et al. 2009). The mutant structure of GyrA pro- tein  was  generated  by  use  of  PyMOL,  a  molecular  visu- alization  tool  (Warren  2002).  The  effects  of  the  mutation

were  then  simulated  by  energy  minimization,  by  use  of  GROMACS  package  4.6.3.  The  3D  structure  of  nalidixic  acid  (DB007779)  was  collected  from  DrugBank  (Wishart  et al. 2006) and used for our investigation.

The  3D  structure  of  GyrA  of  S.  typhimurium  is  not  avail- able  in  the  PDB  database.  Therefore,  phylogenetic  analy- sis was performed to analyze the evolutionary relationship  and similarity between GyrA proteins of different species.  Fourteen GyrA protein sequences of different species were  retrieved from the Uniprot database and used for phyloge- netic  tree  construction.  Initially,  the  sequences  were  con- catenated and multiple sequence alignment was performed  by  using  the  software  clustalW2  (Larkin  et  al.  2007).  Ini- tially,  a  maximum-parsimony  (MP)  (Fitch  1971;  Hartigan  1973)  technique  was  used  to  infer  the  phylogenetic  rela- tionship in our dataset. Subsequently, the results were vali- dated by means of a neighbor-joining (NJ) method (Saitou  and Nei 1987). The MP method is based on a median join- ing  algorithm  (MJ)  whereas  the  NJ  method  is  based  on  a  star decomposition algorithm. For instance, the NJ method  uses  evolutionary  distance  data  to  construct  phylogenetic  trees.  It  is  believed  that  the  NJ  method  is  one  of  the  best  predictors because of its computational speed and the high  accuracy  in  phylogenetic  inference  (Kumar  and  Gadagkar  2000). We made these calculations with the help of MEGA  software version 6 (Tamura et al. 2013). Moreover, a pair- wise alignment technique was also used to infer sequence  similarity  between  the  GyrA  of  E.  coli  and  that  of  S.  typhimurium. Protein stability prediction

The  effect  of  the  S83F  mutation  on  protein  stability  was  analyzed by use of two different computational algorithms,  I-Mutant2.0  and  DUET.  Initially,  the  stability  change  was  examined  at  sequence  level  by  use  of  I-Mutant2.0,  a  neu- ral network-based predictor which estimates protein stabil- ity  changes  on  point  mutation  (Capriotti  et  al.  2005). The  sequence  corresponding  to  2Y3P  was  submitted  to  the  software for prediction. After input of protein three dimen- sional structures the software predicts the direction of pro- tein stability changes on mutation instead of estimating the  relative stability changes on single point mutation (Raghav  and  Sharma  2013).  Subsequently,  a  structural  level  inves- tigation  was  performed  by  using  the  DUET  server.  The  DUET  server  predicts  the  effect  of  mutations  on  protein  structure  stability  by  using  the  Support  Vector  Machines  (SVM)  approach.  Most  importantly,  DUET  consolidates  the results of two complementary approaches (mCSM and  SDM)  for  the  prediction  (Pires  et  al.  2014).  In  this  inves- tigation,  the  protein  structure  (PDB  Code:  2Y3P)  was  uploaded into this software for analysis. It is worth stress- ing  that  programs  such  as  I-Mutant2.0  and  DUET  are  the  most reliable predictors available in the literature in recent  years.

Analysis  of  ligand  binding  site  residues  is  important  for  understanding the affinity of the drug for the protein. The  binding  site  residues  of  the  GyrA  protein  were  examined  by  use  of  the  available  GyrA  complex  structure  from  the  PDB database. The GyrA complex from E. coli (PDB code:  2Y3P)  was  used  for  binding  site  analysis.  Literature  evi- dence was also used for confirmation of the binding pocket  residues in the structure of GyrA. Moreover, the conserva- tion  score  of  the  contacting  residues  were  also  examined  to confirm their occurrence in the binding pocket. ConSurf  software  (Ashkenazy  et  al.  2010)  was  used  to  compute  a  conservation score for all the binding pocket residues in the  2Y3P structure.

Docking  is  a  molecular  modeling  technique  widely  used  to  analyze  the  position,  interaction,  and  orientation  of  ligand molecules bound to a protein. Docking analysis was  used  to  enable  understanding  of  the  pattern  of  interact- ing of nalidixic acid with native and mutant (S83F) GyrA  protein;  the  Autodock4  suite  was  used  for  our  docking  analysis  (Morris  et  al.  2009).  In  the  docking  simulations,  proteins  were  assigned  Kollman  united  atom  charges  and  solvation  values  and  the  ligands  were  assigned  Gasteiger  charge.  Lamarckian  genetic  algorithms  combined  with  genetic  algorithms,  implemented  with  a  150  docking  population  size  and  2.5  million  energy  evaluations,  were  used for docking experiments (Morris et al. 1998). A grid- based  approach  was  used  by  Autodock4  to  approximate  the energy calculations. The docking area was defined by  the  dimension  of  60    60  points  with  grid  spacing  × of 0.375 Å. The grid box was centered on the macromol- ecule  and  covered  almost  the  whole  ligand  binding  site  of  GyrA.  The  docked  results  were  ranked  according  to  the binding free energy. The conformations with the low- est  docked  energy  were  chosen  and  subjected  to  further  analysis. Autodock requires pre-calculated grid maps (one  for each atom type present in the ligand being docked) to  achieve  extremely  fast  docking  calculations.  These  maps  were calculated by Autogrid. A grid map was created with  a 3D lattice of regularly spaced points and centered on the  macromolecule. Autodock tools were also used to analyze  the docked complex structures.

Complete  understanding  of  ligand  binding  mechanisms  are unattainable by use of current experimental techniques.  Molecular dynamics (MD) simulation studies are certainly  helpful for addressing this shortcoming. GROMACS pack- age  4.6.3  was  used  for  MD  simulation  for  the  native  and  mutant  (S83F)  GyrA  complexes  by  implementing  the  GROMOS43a1  force-field  (Hess  et  al.  2008;  Spoel  et  al.  2005).  All  water  molecules  and  the  heteroatoms  were  removed  before  performing  MD  simulation.  The  time- dependent fluctuation and conformational behavior of com- plex  proteins  were  calculated  by  performing  MD  simula- tions.  Structures  were  solvated  by  adoption  of  the  SPC  water  model  and  periodic  boundary  conditions  (Meagher  and  Carlson  2005).  The  ligand  topology  file  was  gener- ated by use of the PRODRG server (Schuttelkopf and Van  Aalten 2004). The GROMOS force field was used to allo- cate  atom  types  and  for  generation  of  a  ligand  topology  file.  Protein–ligand  complex  structures  were  energy  mini- mized  by  using  the  steepest  descent  method.  Na+  counter  ions were added to maintain neutral charge of the system.  Equilibration  of  the  system  was  performed  at  a  constant  temperature  of  300  K  and  1  atm  pressure.  Subsequently,  MD  simulation  was  initiated  for  a  20,000-ps  time  frame  with the equilibrated native and mutant (S83F) complexes.  For  every  picosecond  trajectory,  snapshots  were  saved  for  further  analysis.  Data  such  as  potential  energy,  root  mean  square  deviation  (RMSD),  root  mean  square  fluctuation  (RMSF), and intramolecular H

picosecond  trajectory,  snapshots  were  saved  for  further  analysis.  Data  such  as  potential  energy,  root  mean  square  deviation  (RMSD),  root  mean  square  fluctuation  (RMSF), and intramolecular H-bonds were analyzed.

Phylogenetic analysis of the GyrA protein It  is  believed  that  experimentally  determined  structures  furnish better results in computational analysis than mod- eled  structures.  In  this  study,  the  experimentally  derived  GyrA structure was extracted from the database by means  of phylogenetic analysis. A total of 14 GyrA proteins were  subjected  to  the  analysis  to  infer  the  evolutionary  rela- tionship  among  them.  Initially,  multiple  sequence  align- ment  was  performed  by  use  of  clustalW2  software.  Sub- sequently,  a  phylogenetic  tree  was  constructed,  with  the  help  of  aligned  sequences  of  the  GyrA  protein,  by  using  MEGA6  software  with  the  MP  method.  Confirmation  of  the phylogenetic data was also accomplished by means of  the NJ method. The results are shown in Fig. 1. It is clear  from  the  figure  that  both  methods  place  GyrA  of  E.  coli  and  S.  typhimurium  in  the  same  node.  This  clearly  indi- cates  that  both  the  species  not  only  share  molecular  and  biological  mechanisms  but  also  have  similar  evolutionary  Fig. 1   Phylogenetic tree construction by: a maximum-parsimony method and b neighbor-joining method

distances. Furthermore, pairwise alignment was performed  with  the  aid  of  FASTA  sequences  corresponding  to  both  E. coli (PDB Code 2Y3P) and S. typhimurium GyrA pro- tein. It is noteworthy that S. typhimurium amino acid resi- dues  2  to  522  exactly  match  with  the  E.  coli  sequence.  Most  importantly,  the  mutant  position,  binding  site,  and  domain region were exact matches with the sequence of E.  coli. Therefore, the GyrA structure of E. coli (PDB Code:  2Y3P) could be used as a starting structure for subsequent  computational studies. Because protein stability is believed to be the most impor- tant factor in drug binding and in other biological activity  (Jaenicke  1991),  we  studied  the  effect  of  S83F  mutation  on the GyrA protein with the help of I-Mutant 2.0 and the  DUET  algorithm.  The  results  are  shown  in  Table  1.  The  I-Mutant2.0  software  predicts  the  direction  in  which  the  mutation shifts the stability of the protein (the DDG sign)  and DDG-associated values in kcal/mol. Understanding of binding site residues information is crucial  in molecular simulation studies. In this study, we extracted the  contacting residues in the 2Y3P structure of the GyrA protein  from the available literature evidence. The literature evidence  indicates  that  amino  acid  residues  Lys  42,  Val  44,  His  45,  His 78, Pro 79, His 80, Gly 81, Arg 91, Ser 171, and Ser 172  could  be  important  for  making  ligand  contacts  in  the  GyrA  protein  (Sahu  et  al.  2013;  Hearnshaw  et  al.  2014).  The  site  of S83F and the key residues are shown in Fig. 2a. It is also  believed that binding site residues are those which are highly  conserved  in  the  protein  structure  (Gromiha  et  al.  2011).  Therefore, we also confirmed the binding site residues from  the  conservation  scores.  The  software  ConSurf  (Ashkenazy  et al. 2010) was used for this purpose. The results predicted  Fig. 2   a The mutation site  Ser 83 (Blue) and other crucial  amino acid (red) residues in the  GyrA protein. b Superimposed  structures of native (green)  and mutant (S83F) (red) GyrA  protein by ConSurf revealed that His 45, Arg 91, and Ser 172 were  present in a highly conserved region (conservation score of 9)  of the GyrA protein structure. Hence, we specified these resi- dues as binding site residues in our docking analysis.

The docking study was executed with the purpose of under- standing  the  affinity  of  nalidixic  acid  for  the  native  and  mutant (S83F) GyrA protein. The mutant GyrA protein struc- ture was generated by use of PyMOL software. Initially, both  the native (PDB code: 2Y3P) and mutant type GyrA protein  were energy-minimized by using GROMACS package 4.6.3,  by adopting the GROMOS96 force field. Subsequently, dock- ing experiments were executed by use of AutoDock4 software  to investigate the binding affinity between nalidixic acid and  the target proteins. It should be noted that Autodock predicts  binding  pose  accurately  (Dhanik  et  al.  2012).  Autodock  is  widely used software with several examples of successful use  (Huang  et  al.  2008;  Du  et  al.  2009). Autodock  provides  the  10 best conformations on the basis of the binding energy. The  best complex of the ligand with the target protein is regarded  as that with the lowest energy. Therefore, binding energy cor- responding to the best conformation was considered to under- stand  the  efficiency  of  the  interaction  of  nalidixic  acid  with  the target protein. The energy of binding to the native protein  was found to be  7.70  kcal/mol whereas that of binding to  − 3.80 kcal/mol (Table 2).  the mutant protein was found to be  The lower binding free energy of nalidixic acid with the S83F  structure indicates less effective binding of nalidixic acid to  the mutant (S83F) GyrA protein. The superimposed structure  Table 2   Docking results for nalidixic acid with native and mutant (S83F) GyrA protein Fig. 3   Interaction of nalidixic acid with a native and b mutant (S83F) GyrA

of  native  and  mutant  (S83F)  GyrA  is  shown  in  the  Fig.  2b.  The binding energy results were further confirmed by deter- mining the prevalence of intermolecular contacts in the com- plex  structures,  by  use  of  LIGPLOT  (Laskowski  and  Swin- dells 2011). The result is shown in Fig. 3. The dotted line in  the figure indicates the hydrogen bonding pattern and the red  arc is representative of hydrophobic contacts in the complex  structures.  It  is  evident  from  the  figure  that  nalidixic  acid  forms  one  hydrogen  bond  interaction,  with  Arg  91,  in  the  native  type  GyrA  whereas  a  single  Gln  267–nalidixic  acid  hydrogen  bonding  interaction  was  observed  in  the  mutant  (S83F)  nalidixic  acid  complex.  This  indicates  that  muta- tion  alters  the  conformation  of  the  binding  pocket  residues  because  nalidixic  acid  is  able  to  maintain  hydrogen  bond- ing with the highly conserved Arg 91 only in the native type  whereas this interaction is not observed in the mutant (S83F)  GyrA protein. Moreover, the shorter bond length (2.83 Å) and  the interaction with the charged amino acid (Arg) residue also  facilitates stronger binding of nalidixic acid to the native type  rather than the mutant (3.02 Å) type GyrA protein (Rajagopal  Intermolecular  energy (kcal/mol) Electrostatic   energy (kcal/mol)

and Vishveshwara 2005). In fact, Arg 91 is moved away from  the binding site as a result of the S83F mutation and the dis- tance between Arg 91 and nalidixic acid in the mutant system  was found to be 6.2 Å. The increase in the distance between  Arg  91  and  nalidixic  acid  in  the  mutant  complex  compared  with the native complex results in the loss of intermolecular  interaction.  Further,  the  available  literature  evidence  clearly  indicates  that  Ser  83  is  one  of  the  highly  conserved  amino  acid  residues  in  the  GyrA  structure  (Pan  et  al.  1996).  The  mutation  at  this  conserved  position  significantly  affects  the  stability and function of the protein (Li et al. 2009; Liu et al.  2014; Abrol et al. 2014). Further, mutation introduces a non- polar residue, resulting also in a change in the hydrophobicity  of the target protein (Venselaar et al. 2010). Most importantly,  we observed 180° flipping of ligand binding because of a sin- gle mutation (S83F) in the GyrA protein. It is worth mention- ing that our results are the first literature evidence revealing  180° flipping of ligand binding because of single amino acid  mutation. Overall, the results from our analysis and the avail- able  evidence  clearly  indicates  that  S83F  mutation  not  only  Total internal  energy (kcal/mol) Torsional free  energy (kcal/mol) Binding free  energy (kcal/mol) Fig. 4   Molecular dynamics  trajectories of native (black) and  S83F (red) GyrA throughout the  simulation time. a Energy plot b  RMSD analysis. c RMSF analy- sis. d Intramolecular hydrogen  bonds in native protein. e  Intramolecular hydrogen bonds  in S83F protein affects protein stability but also significantly affects binding  of nalidixic acid to the GyrA protein. Molecular dynamics simulation

Molecular  dynamics  simulations  were  performed  to  con- firm the effect of the S83F mutation on GyrA structure and  function.  The  molecular  dynamics  simulation  study  was  performed with the native type and mutant (S83F) nalidixic  acid  complexes.  GROMACS  package  4.6.3  implemented  with  GROMOS43a1  force  field  was  used  for  this  purpose  (Hess et al. 2008; Spoel et al. 2005). The trajectories were  archived  for  analysis  of  potential  energy,  RMSD,  RMSF,  and  intramolecular  H-bonds.  The  stability  of  the  complex  during  the  simulation  period  was  analyzed  by  means  of  energy  plots.  The  plots  for  the  variation  of  the  energy  of

the biomolecules along the MD simulation showed that the  energy of the protein–drug complex stabilizes after the first  picosecond of simulation (Fig. 4a), with negligible energy  variation thereafter, indicating that the total energy remains  constant,  thus  suggesting  structural  stabilization.  The  RMSD trajectories corresponding to the native and mutant  (S83F)  complex  structures  during  the  simulation  period  are shown in Fig. 4b. The deviation of the trajectory in the  first  1500  ps  was  higher  for  the  mutant  (~0.44  nm)  than  for the native (~0.18 nm) GyrA protein complex. Between  1500 and 4000 ps, deviation from the original structure was  less for both the native and mutant (S83F). After 4000 ps,  the  mutant  (S83F)  system  RMSD  was,  again,  larger  and  reached  a  value  of  ~0.5  nm  whereas  the  RMSD  value  for  the  native  system  was  ~0.25  nm.  The  RMSD  fluctua- tion was found to be significantly less for both native and  mutant  systems  in  the  simulation  range  7000–10,000  ps.  However, between 10,000 and 17,000 ps, the mutant fluctu- ated more, with the RMSD reaching ~0.44 nm whereas for  the native system the RMSD value was ~0.24 nm. Finally,  at the end of the simulation period, 20,000 ps, the RMSD  of  the  native  system  was  ~0.25  nm  whereas  that  for  the  mutant system was ~0.58 nm. Most importantly, the RMSD  value  for  the  mutant  system  was  higher  than  that  for  the  native system throughout the simulation period. The higher  RMSD for the mutant–nalidixic acid complex clearly signi- fies formation of a less stable conformation than the native– nalidixic acid complex.

Residue  dynamic  activity  was  analyzed  by  using  the  RMSF  trajectories  for  both  native  and  mutant  (S83F)  type complex (Fig. 4c), including flexibility of the amino  acid  binding  site  region  and  mutational  region.  In  both  cases, the flexibility is significantly higher for the mutant  (S83F)  type  than  for  the  native  system.  For  instance,  the  RMSF  value  for  residues  50–180  in  the  mutant  type  was  ~0.25 nm whereas it was only ~0.2 nm for the native sys- tem. We  also  observed  marginal  fluctuations  for  both  the  native  and  mutant  systems  between  positions  180  and  350.  Most  importantly,  higher  fluctuations  were  observed  for the mutant system (~0.5 nm), particularly at positions  350–522,  than  for  the  native  system  (~0.4  nm).  These  observations indicate that the flexibility of the amino acid  residues  in  the  GyrA  structure  was  substantially  affected  by  the  mutation  at  position  83.  Finally,  hydrogen  bond  trajectories were also generated for our native and mutant  structure  to  enable  understanding  of  structural  integrity.  The results are shown in Fig. 4d, e. It is clear from the fig- ure that the mutant structure is able to maintain a greater  number of intramolecular interactions than the native type.  For instance, the mutant type structure maintained an aver- age  of  400  hydrogen  bonds  during  the  simulation  time.  On  the  other  hand,  the  native  type  structure  maintained  an  average  of  390  intramolecular  contacts  during  the

simulation  period.  The  larger  number  of  interactions  for  the mutant (S83F) GyrA protein is indicative of the rigid- ity of the structure. It is worth stressing that this observa- tion correlates well with the flexibility and hydrogen bond  data analysis. Overall, the simulation study led to the con- clusion  that  the  rigidity  of  the  structure  changes  because  of the S83F mutation. The rigidity of the structure will, in  turn,  affect  the  binding  of  nalidixic  acid  and  thus  confer  resistance to the drug.

In this study we analyzed the mechanism of nalidixic acid  resistance in salmonellosis by use of molecular simulation  techniques. Initially, protein stability was examined by use  of  two  different  algorithms,  I-Mutant2.0  and  DUET.  Sub- sequently,  the  effect  on  function  was  examined  by  means  of  a  molecular  simulation  study.  The  results  from  our  docking  study  reveal  that  the  S83F  mutation  in  the  GyrA  structure  reduces  binding  affinity  for  nalidixic  acid.  Most  importantly,  we  observed  180°  flipping  of  ligand  binding  because  of  a  single  mutation  (S83F)  of  the  GyrA  protein.  This  is  the  first  observation  of  such  an  effect  of  a  single  mutation and warrants further investigation. The structural  analysis indicated that the S83F mutation certainly affects  the  prevalence  of  intermolecular  contacts  in  the  complex  structure.  For  instance,  our  analysis  clearly  indicates  that  Arg 91 of GyrA was needed to make strong hydrogen bond  interactions with nalidixic acid. Molecular dynamics simu- lation results also confirmed more effective binding of nali- dixic acid with native type GyrA than with the S83F GyrA  structure.  Overall,  we  hope  these  findings  will  be  useful  for  pharmacists  attempting  to  develop  better  antibacterial  drugs for treatment of gastroenteritis.
